# Verin Mathwin · the Brown who wore the enemy's coat for seventy years

Verin Mathwin appears, for most of her life, as exactly what the White Tower takes her to be: a mild and curious scholar of the Brown Ajah, given to study and quiet patience. Beneath that gentle surface she carries the deepest secret in the saga. Long ago she was coerced into the Black Ajah by an oath, and rather than be destroyed by it, she chose to turn her captivity into a weapon against the Shadow that bound her.

For seventy years she lived a double life inside the enemy's ranks, recording the Black Ajah's members and their plans from within. It was the long, lonely labor of a scholar turned spy: every name set down, every scheme noted, all of it gathered against a single moment of release. To wear the enemy's coat that long without flinching was its own form of endurance, sustained by a purpose she could share with no one.

When her work was complete, she freed herself the only way the oath allowed. She drank poison, and as the Oath's hold dissolved with her life, she handed the entire list to Egwene with her dying breath. In that act she struck the single most devastating blow against the Shadow's infiltration of the Tower, naming in death the hidden enemies she could never name in life.

Her emergence is spiritual: hers is a story of redemption and sacrifice in service of the Light, a soul that turned coercion into salvation and gave everything in a final, freely chosen act of faith for the turning of the Wheel.
